#!/usr/bin/env python3
"""easy_build: scaffold a hermetic Bazel project (cpp, java, python, go, rust,
kotlin, scala, or haskell).

No host toolchain is ever invoked. Bazel downloads a pinned, prebuilt
toolchain distribution for the target platform and uses only that:

    cpp     -- clang/LLVM, via the `toolchains_llvm` module
    java    -- a remote JDK, via the `rules_java` module
    python  -- a standalone CPython (python-build-standalone), via `rules_python`,
               with pip dependency management and a self-contained zip binary
    go      -- a remote Go SDK, via the `rules_go` module
    rust    -- a remote rustc/cargo toolchain, via the `rules_rust` module
    kotlin  -- a remote kotlinc, via the `rules_kotlin` module (JVM target: also
               pins its own hermetic remotejdk, composing with `java` if present)
    scala   -- a remote Scala compiler, via the `rules_scala` module (JVM
               target: also pins its own hermetic remotejdk, as with kotlin)
    haskell -- a remote GHC, via the `rules_haskell` module

Languages compose: running `init` for another language adds to the shared
`MODULE.bazel` / `.bazelrc` rather than replacing them, and each language's
sample program lives in its own `example/<language>/` package, so
`example/cpp`, `example/java`, `example/python`, `example/go`, `example/rust`,
`example/kotlin`, `example/scala`, and `example/haskell` can all coexist.

Supported target platforms (native builds, one platform per Bazel invocation):
    linux_x86_64    linux_aarch64
    macos_x86_64    macos_aarch64
"""
